'''Findlay Kenneth Curtis''' (born 9 June 2006)<!--Do not change without reason. In this source, a Rangers official states that the often cited birthdate of 1 October is not true. This is backed by friends and family who can confirm his birthday as the 9th of June. https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/rangers/latest-rangers-news/findlay-curtis-fake-news-confession-as-rangers-teenager-comes-of-age-literally-after-ibrox-heroics-5239438 --> is a Scottish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]], on loan from [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], and the [[Scotland national football team|Scotland national team]].<ref name="FC">{{Soccerway|id=findlay-curtis/864385}}</ref>

==Club career==
Curtis joined [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]' academy at age 6, having impressed at a football school run by the club.<ref name=academy/> In July 2022, he signed his first professional contract and was promoted to Rangers' under-18 team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=Jordan |title=Why Rangers are recruiting 'emerging talent' – after banking almost £10m |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/3353107/2022/07/02/rangers-recruitment-emerging-talent-10m/ |access-date=23 January 2025 |work=[[The Athletic]] |date=2 July 2022|url-access=subscription}}</ref> His deal was extended in January 2023 to last until June 2024.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Irvine |first1=David |title=Five Rangers youngsters agree Ibrox contract extensions |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/23241223.five-rangers-youngsters-agree-ibrox-contract-extensions/ |access-date=23 January 2025 |work=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |date=10 January 2023}}</ref> On 1 May 2024 he scored a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] to equalise as Rangers came from behind to win the [[Scottish Youth Cup]] against [[Aberdeen F.C. Reserves and Academy|Aberdeen]] at [[Hampden Park]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Idessane |first1=Kheredine |title=Rangers hit back against Aberdeen to win Youth Cup |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c51n37x49rdo |access-date=23 January 2025 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=1 May 2024}}</ref> On 28 May 2024, Curtis signed a further extension until 2025.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://x.com/RFC_Youth/status/1795424785129947242|title=Rangers Academy can today announce Findlay Curtis has signed a contract extension until summer 2025.|work=Rangers FC|publisher=X.com|date=28 May 2024}}</ref>

Curtis was part of the [[Rangers F.C. B Team and Academy|Rangers B Team]] in the [[Scottish Challenge Cup]]. He scored twice in a 4–1 home win over [[Stenhousemuir F.C.|Stenhousemuir]] on 22 October 2024, in the fourth round of the cup.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kearney |first1=Ben |title=£10 million team too much for Stenhousemuir as Rangers B seal SPFL Trust Trophy quarter-final spot |url=https://www.falkirkherald.co.uk/sport/football/ps10-million-team-too-much-for-stenhousemuir-as-rangers-b-seal-spfl-trust-trophy-quarter-final-spot-4836911 |access-date=23 January 2025 |work=[[Falkirk Herald]] |date=23 October 2024}}</ref>

On 19 January 2025, Curtis made his first-team debut in the fourth round of the [[Scottish Cup]], in a 5–0 win over [[Highland Football League]] club [[Fraserburgh F.C.|Fraserburgh]]. He came on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in the 62nd minute and assisted the last goal, completing [[Cyriel Dessers]]' hat-trick.<ref>{{cite news |title=Dessers hits hat-trick as Rangers beat Fraserburgh in David v Goliath tie |url=https://news.stv.tv/sport/cyriel-dessers-hits-hat-trick-as-rangers-breeze-past-fraserburgh-in-david-v-goliath-scottish-cup-clash |access-date=23 January 2025 |agency=PA Sport |publisher=[[STV News]] |date=19 January 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rangers 5&ndash;0 Fraserburgh |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c3w8qwlv498t |access-date=23 January 2025 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=19 January 2025}}</ref> Four days later he made his European debut in the [[UEFA Europa League]] [[2024–25 UEFA Europa League league phase|league phase]], again from the bench for the final half-hour of a 2–1 loss away to [[Manchester United]]; according to Ewan Paton of ''[[The National (Scotland)|The National]]'', he gave a good performance in "difficult circumstances".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Paton |first1=Ewan |title=Rangers player ratings in Europa League loss vs Man Utd |url=https://www.thenational.scot/sport/24881017.rangers-player-ratings-europa-league-loss-vs-man-utd/ |access-date=23 January 2025 |work=[[The National (Scotland)|The National]] |date=23 January 2025}}</ref>

On 29 January 2025, Curtis signed a contract extension of undisclosed length.<ref>{{cite news |title='Proud day' as Curtis signs contract extension |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/ce3nx5kel55o |access-date=30 January 2025 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 January 2025}}</ref> Eighteen days later, he made his [[Scottish Premiership]] debut in the last minute of a 3–1 win away to [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pattullo |first1=Alan |title=Philippe Clement spared Ibrox vitriol as Rangers agenda moves on with no need for Jose Mourinho's laundry basket |url=https://www.scotsman.com/sport/football/rangers/latest-rangers-news/philippe-clement-spared-ibrox-vitriol-as-rangers-agenda-moves-on-with-no-need-for-jose-mourinhos-laundry-basket-5002619 |access-date=23 February 2025 |work=The Scotsman |date=21 February 2025}}</ref>

On 22 July 2025, Curtis scored his first goal for Rangers in a [[UEFA Champions League]] qualifier against [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] at [[Ibrox Stadium|Ibrox]].<ref name="Age"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Rangers 2-0 Panathinaikos|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cm2lgl1x1vpt|publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 July 2025}}</ref> He started the game on the left side of the attack, in [[Russell Martin (footballer)|Russell Martin's]] first game as manager.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McPheat |first1=Nick |title='Cool cat' Curtis ignites Martin's Rangers reign |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c0m8d11y24vo |access-date=27 July 2025 |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> His first league goal came on 24 August as the equaliser in a 1–1 draw away to [[St Mirren F.C.|St Mirren]], as a substitute for [[Joe Rothwell]].<ref>{{cite news |title='I have to trust him': Martin queries Igamane injury claim after Rangers draw |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/aug/24/st-mirren-rangers-scottish-premiership-match-report |access-date=1 February 2026 |work=The Guardian |date=24 August 2025}}</ref>

On 30 January 2026, having achieved three goals and two assists in 21 Rangers appearances, Curtis joined fellow Scottish Premiership club [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]] on loan for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Killie sign striker Hugill & loan Rangers winger Curtis |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c3dm3k9kkxzo |access-date=1 February 2026 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 January 2026}}</ref> He scored five goals in 14 games, including four in the last five fixtures, as "Killie" avoided relegation in 10th place.<ref name=oneill/>

==International career==
Curtis made his first appearance for the [[Scotland national under-21 football team|Scotland under-21]] team on 5 September 2025, as a 77th-minute substitute for [[Daniel Kelly (footballer, born 2005)|Daniel Kelly]] in a 2–0 loss away to the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]] in [[2027 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.scottishfa.co.uk/players/?pid=248302&lid=5  |title=Findlay Curtis |website=Scottish FA |accessdate=16 March 2026}}</ref> 

Curtis was included in the full [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] squad for the first time in March 2026, for [[Exhibition game|friendly matches]] against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and the [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cpd8w4xg991o |title=Scotland squad: Kilmarnock winger Findlay Curtis called up |website=BBC Sport |date=16 March 2026 |accessdate=16 March 2026}}</ref> He made his debut on 28 March against Japan at [[Hampden Park]], replacing [[Tommy Conway]] for the last nine minutes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=George |title=What might Scotland change for Ivory Coast test? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/ce84ml83x14o |access-date=29 March 2026 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=29 March 2026}}</ref> He was called up for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] in North America; manager [[Steve Clarke]] praised his decision to move on loan to Kilmarnock for regular playing time.<ref name=oneill>{{cite news |last1=O'Neill |first1=George |title= How Curtis timed run to perfection for World Cup place|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/ce8pn4jjjzko|access-date=19 May 2026 |publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=19 May 2026}}</ref> He scored his first Scotland goal in a friendly against [[Curaçao national football team|Curaçao]].

